Alright, let’s take it one step further. Imagine the story as a solid object in meaning-space, but the audience never sees the object directly. Instead, each episode shows a shadow of it from a different direction. Only by combining the shadows can the viewer reconstruct the true shape.

This idea is sometimes called a Rashomon-style narrative, but you can extend it into something closer to semantic tomography—like scanning an object from multiple angles to rebuild its interior.

⸻

1. The Hidden Core Event

At the center is one true sequence of events:

The traveler obtains the key.
The guardian confronts them.
A storm damages the city.
The gate is opened.
Something escapes.

But the audience never sees this full chain directly.

⸻

2. Episode as “Shadow Projection”

Each episode reveals only part of the event, filtered through someone’s perspective.

Episode A — The Traveler

Focus: intention and hope
	•	The traveler believes opening the gate will save the city.
	•	The storm seems like an unrelated disaster.

Episode B — The Guardian

Focus: duty and fear
	•	The guardian knows the gate seals something dangerous.
	•	The traveler appears reckless.

Episode C — The Citizen

Focus: rumor and consequence
	•	The storm and the palace theft appear linked.
	•	People speculate about what really happened.

Episode D — The Archivist (years later)

Focus: incomplete records
	•	Fragments of all the stories exist, but none fully agree.

Each episode is truthful, but only partially.

⸻

3. Reconstruction by the Audience

As viewers watch multiple episodes, they begin mentally assembling the pieces:

Traveler’s version
+ Guardian’s version
+ Citizen’s version
+ Historical fragments
--------------------------------
≈ the real sequence of events

The audience becomes the one solving the puzzle.

⸻

4. Why It Feels Powerful

This structure mirrors how we understand real events:
	•	No one sees everything.
	•	Each participant has limited information.
	•	History is reconstructed from partial accounts.

So the story feels intellectually engaging and realistic.

⸻

5. Visualizing the Idea

Think of the real story as a 3-D object.

3-D narrative object
        ↓
Episode viewpoints
        ↓
2-D projections (stories we hear)

Only when you combine the projections can you infer the object.

⸻

6. Combining With Your Dice Model

You now have three interacting layers:
	1.	Meaning Die – political, psychological, mythic, etc.
	2.	Perspective Die – traveler, guardian, citizen, historian.
	3.	Projection Layer – each episode reveals only part of events.

Together they form something like:

Events
  × Perspective
  × Interpretation
  × Time

A huge space of possible readings.

⸻

7. Why This Works Best for Series

A series can gradually reveal the structure:
	•	Early episodes: clear but incomplete stories
	•	Middle episodes: contradictions appear
	•	Later episodes: patterns emerge
	•	Final episodes: viewers reconstruct the hidden narrative

The result is a story that rewards attention and reinterpretation.

